point mass &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(m1\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math"&gt;\(m2\)&lt;/span&gt; being at the ends of the two pendulum.
&lt;div id='trailer' class='sketchContainer'&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4&gt;Chaos&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a simple, maybe even contrived example of a chaotic system. If even a slight difference is
given in otherwise identical two systems, the time evolution is drastically different for these
systems. As seen in this one below  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span id='slight_1' class='sketchContainer'&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span id='slight_2' class='sketchContainer'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;button id='playS'onclick='simPlay()'&gt;play&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you can see, even though the initial configurations are identical as far as we can tell, as the
time progresses, these systems have wildly different configurations.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is amazing!&lt;/p&gt;
